KW  - Segmented labor markets
KW  - Fiscal policy
KW  - Minimum wages
AB  - This paper analyzes the macroeconomic effects of fiscal and labor market policies in a developing economy with an informal sector and a heterogeneous work force. A permanent reduction in government spending on nontraded goods leads in the long run to a depreciation of the real exchange rate, a fall in the market-clearing wage for unskilled labor, an increase in output of traded goods, and a lower stock of net foreign assets. A permanent reduction in the minimum wage improves competitiveness, and expands the formal sector. The effect of changes in unemployment benefits are also analyzed.
